section.subsection:
			 Sage Commands



 				When written as column vectors, vectors behave like n \times 1 matrices, and they can be coded as such in Sage. As a shortcut, you can specify the number of rows (number of entries in the vector) and then include a single list of the entries.
			
 			
 				
 					u=matrix(3, [2,4,6]);
					v=matrix(5, [1,3,5,7,9]);
					show(u);
					show(v)
 				
 			
			
			
				


				However, we often want to treat vectors as vectors specifically. In Sage, we use the vector command, which is similar to the matrix command. We do not need to state the number of entries with this command; we simply list them out. Note also that Sage displays the result in row form (an alternative display form discussed in the textbook), but they are treated the same as column vectors.
				
	 			
	 				
	 					u=vector([2,4,6]);
						v=vector([1,3,5,7,9]);
						show(u);
						show(v);
						v
	 				
	 			
				
				


				The cell below demonstrates how to create linear combinations of vectors. Note that writing "5v1" will cause an error; a multiplication symbol is needed between the scalar and the vector.
			
 			
 			
 				
 					v1=vector([1,-3,4]);
					v2=vector([2,5,1]);
					print(v1+v2);
					print(v1-v2);
					print(5*v1);
					print(3*v1+7*v2);
					print(-3*v1-4*v2)
 				
 			
			
			One nice consequence of Sage vectors is that we can easily create matrices out of them. We will usually want to create matrices whose columns are some given vectors. This is done using the column_matrix command and demonstrated below.
 			
 				
 					u1=vector([1,2,3]);
					u2=vector([4,5,6]);
					u3=vector([7,8,9]);
					A=column_matrix([u1,u2,u3]);
					show(A)

			 Sage Commands



 				Sage naturally understands multiplication of a vector by a matrix using the usual multiplication symbol (shift+8 on most keyboards). (Remember that Sage displays vectors in row form with parentheses, but correctly treats them as column vectors)
			
 			
 				
 					A=matrix([[1,2,3], [4,5,6], [7,8,9]]);
					B=matrix([[1,3,5], [7,8,9]]);
					v=vector([-1,3,-5]);
					show("A=",A," B=",B," v=",v)
					show("Av=",A*v)
					show("Bv=",B*v)
 				
 			
			


				Note that the dimensions have to match up (the number of columns of the matrix should match the number of entries in the vector); if they do not, then Sage will output an error (which you can see by executing the code below).
			
			
 			
 				
 					C=matrix([[1,2],[3,4], [5,6]])
					show("C=",C)
					v=vector([-1,3,-5]);
					show("v=",v)
					C*v
 				
 			
			
				
			
			As a reminder, if vectors are already defined, you can create a matrix using them. To make a matrix with the vectors as columns, use the column_matrix command, shown below. To make a matrix with the vectors as rows, just use the matrix command with the vectors given inside brackets.
 			
 				
 					u1=vector([1,2,3]);
					u2=vector([4,5,6]);
					u3=vector([7,8,9]);
					A=column_matrix([u1,u2,u3]);
					show("vectors as columns:",A)
					B=matrix([u1,u2,u3]);
					show("vectors as rows:",B)

subsection.p:
 				Applying a matrix transformation to a vector involves multiplying a vector by a matrix. The cell below reviews these commands. Answering questions about these matrix transformations will often require row reduction, which we continue to do using the .rref() method.
				
				
	 			
	 				
	 					v=vector([1,2,3,4]);
						A=column_matrix([[1,3], [2,4], [5,1], [-1,-6]]);
						show("A=",A);
						show("v=",v);
						show("The image of v under the action by A is Av=",A*v)

 				There is no Sage command for "find the standard matrix"; we have to do that part ourselves. Once we have the standard matrix, we can row reduce it using .rref() and analyze it as we have been doing. However, we can use Sage to explore the geometric actions of linear transformations (this will be the main focus of Project 3). The code below creates the letter N, plots it, and then plots a linear transformation applied to the letter N. Try changing the entries of A in the third cell to see what effect it has.
			
				
	 			
	 				
	 					d=matrix(QQ, 2, 9, [[0, 0.5, 0.5, 6, 6, 5.5, 5.5, 0, 0], [0, 0, 6.42, 0, 8, 8, 1.58, 8, 0]]); 
						show(d); #each column represents a point in the plane
						
	 				
	 			
				
				
				
					
						N_0=list_plot(d.columns(), plotjoined=true, aspect_ratio=1, color='purple'); 
						N_0 # the above command "connects the dots" to create a picture
					
				
				
				
					
						A=matrix(QQ, [[1,0.25,],[0,1]]); show(A) #the standard matrix of a linear transformation
						d_1=A*d; #apply the transformation to the original points
						N_1=list_plot(d_1.columns(), plotjoined=true, aspect_ratio=1, color='blue'); 
						# the above command "connects the dots" on the transformed image
						N_0+N_1 #display the original image and the transformed image

Matrix addition:


	
		A=matrix([[1,3,5], [2,4,6]]);
		B=matrix([[1,-1], [4,2]]);
		C=matrix([[5,6], [1,3]]);
		show("B=", B)
		show("C=", C)
		show("B+C=", B+C); #add matrices using +

 I encourage you to change the definition of A to see the effect of doing the transformations repeatedly or in a different order. To see the definition of A, scroll down in the Sage cell below.
			
 			
 				
 					d=matrix(QQ, 2, 9, [[0, 0.5, 0.5, 6, 6, 5.5, 5.5, 0, 0], [0, 0, 6.42, 0, 8, 8, 1.58, 8, 0]]); 
					N_0=list_plot(d.columns(), plotjoined=true, aspect_ratio=1, color='purple'); 
					
					# a horizontal shear matrix:
					S=matrix(RDF, [[1,0.25,],[0,1]]); 
					
					# a rotation matrix:
					R=matrix(RDF, [[cos(pi/4), -sin(pi/4)], [sin(pi/4), cos(pi/4)]]); 
					
					# a dilation matrix
					D=matrix(RDF, [[2, 0], [0,2]]); 
					
					# shear, followed by rotation, followed by dilation
					A=D*R*S; 
					d_1=A*d; #transformation applied
					
					N_1=list_plot(d_1.columns(), plotjoined=true, aspect_ratio=1, color='blue'); 
					N_0+N_1
